<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Festuca brachyphylla </i>is a perennial bunchgrass with smooth, glabrous to sparsely hairy leaves. Plants are strongly caespitose. Plants establish tillers within their compact root crowns as they grow. This circumpolar species grows from arctic to alpine elevations on many landforms, elevations, aspects, and soil types, and it occupies the widest range of habitats of any fescue in North America. It is phenotypically plastic and responds dramatically to additional nutrients in the environment (Aiken et al. 1997). California plants are <i>F. brachyphylla </i>ssp. <i>coloradensis. <br/>
<br/>
</i>The alliance occurs on windswept alpine summits in California, where <i>F. brachyphylla </i>typically associates with cushion plants such as <i>Eriogonum ovalifolium</i>. It also occurs in rocky areas where snow tends to accumulate, associating with species such as <i>Penstemon davidsonii</i>. The drier windswept stands bear similarities to the <i>Ericameria discoidea</i>-<i>Hulsea algida </i>alliance, whereas more mesic stands are more similar to the <i>Carex helleri </i>alliance in Yosemite National Park (Sawyer and Keeler-Wolf 2007). The National Vegetation Classification (NatureServe 2007a) recognizes the alliance in the Cascades and Rocky Mountains; we need further sampling and analysis to clarify relationships with similar alliances in the California mountains. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
